.TH "uncat" "1" 
.SH NAME
uncat \- continuously reads stdin, splits up the data either by timeout
or number of bytes read to process it
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]uncat\f[R] [\-vo] [\-t \f[I]seconds\f[R]] [\-s \f[I]size\f[R]]
\f[I]prog\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]uncat\f[R] continuously reads stdin and repeatedly processes the
data either after \f[I]seconds\f[R] timeout or maximal number of bytes
\f[I]size\f[R] read.
To process the data, \f[B]uncat\f[R] starts \f[I]prog\f[R] and feeds the
data into \f[I]prog\f[R]\[aq]s standard input.
\f[I]prog\f[R]\[aq]s standard output is redirected to standard error.
\f[B]uncat\f[R] never writes to standard output.
.PP
\f[I]prog\f[R] consist of one or more arguments.
.PP
If \f[I]prog\f[R] exits non\-zero, \f[B]uncat\f[R] prints an error
message, discards the data and continues to read stdin.
.PP
Note that \f[B]uncat\f[R] is not crash proof.
.PP
\f[B]uncat\f[R] is used to run the \f[I]socklog\-notify\f[R] service.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
verbose.
Print verbose messages to stderr.
.TP
\f[B]\-o\f[R]
once.
Exit on end of input.
Normally \f[B]uncat\f[R] continues waiting for data on standard input,
even on end of file.
.TP
\f[B]\-t\f[R] \f[I]seconds\f[R]
timeout.
Set the timeout to \f[I]seconds\f[R] seconds.
Default is 300.
.TP
\f[B]\-s\f[R] \f[I]size\f[R]
Set the maximal number of bytes to \f[I]size\f[R].
Default is 1024.
.SH SIGNALS
If \f[B]uncat\f[R] receives a TERM signal, it starts to process the data
in memory and exits as soon as possible.
.PP
\f[B]uncat\f[R] also does this on end of input if the \f[B]\-o\f[R]
option was given.
.SH EXIT CODES
\f[B]uncat\f[R] returns 0 after receiving a TERM signal.
\f[B]uncat\f[R] returns 111 on error.
